GIT FLOW RULES

1. Naming format
- Use lowercase letters and hyphens.
- Keep names concise and descriptive.
- Use only: a-z, 0-9, hyphen (-), and slash (/).
- Do not use spaces, underscores, punctuation, or special characters.
- Do not use consecutive hyphens ("--").
- Do not end branch names with a hyphen.

2. Allowed branch prefixes
- feature/   : new functionality
- bugfix/    : non-critical bug fixes
- hotfix/    : critical production fixes
- release/   : release preparation
- docs/      : documentation changes

3. Pattern
- <prefix>/<short-description>

4. Examples
- feature/login-system
- bugfix/header-styling
- hotfix/critical-security-issue
- release/1.0.1
- docs/api-endpoints

5. Release versioning
- Use Semantic Versioning: MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH.
- Release branch names must use dotted versions: release/1.2.0.
- Do not use hyphenated numeric versions for releases (for example, release/1-2-0).

6. Pre-release rules
- Pre-releases must append a label and numeric counter to a valid SemVer base.
- Allowed labels: alpha, beta, rc.
- Format: <major>.<minor>.<patch>-<label>.<number>
- Valid examples:
  - 1.3.0-alpha.1
  - 1.3.0-beta.2
  - 1.3.0-rc.1
- Pre-release branch examples:
  - release/1.3.0-rc.1
  - release/2.0.0-beta.1

7. Source and target branch rules
- feature/* branches must be created from develop and merged back into develop.
- release/* branches must be created from develop and merged into both main and develop.
- hotfix/* branches must be created from main and merged into both main and develop.

8. Branch lifecycle rules
- One branch should map to one issue/task.
- Delete feature, release, and hotfix branches after merge.
- Keep release and hotfix branches short-lived.

9. Merge policy
- Direct commits to main and develop are not allowed.
- All changes must go through a pull request.
- At least one reviewer approval is required before merge.
- Use one merge strategy consistently across the repo (squash or merge commit).

10. Quality gates
- Build must pass before merge.
- Automated tests must pass before merge.
- No high-severity lint or security issues are allowed at merge time.

11. Commit and PR conventions
- Use Conventional Commits (feat:, fix:, chore:, docs:, refactor:, test:).
- Include issue/ticket ID in commit message or PR title when available.

12. Tagging rules
- Final release tags are created from main only and must follow: v<major>.<minor>.<patch>.
- Pre-release tags must follow: v<major>.<minor>.<patch>-<label>.<number>.

13. Invalid examples
- Feature/New-Login            (uppercase)
- feature/new_login            (underscore)
- feature//new-login           (double slash)
- feature/new--login           (double hyphen)
- feature/new-login-           (trailing hyphen)
- release/1-2-0                (hyphenated release version)
- release/1.2.0-preview.1      (unsupported pre-release label)